\f0\fs24 \cf0 Tips for learning the most from people, interview-style (via Kasey):\
Prepare your goals, directions, and purposes, but start with small talk to avoid your interviewee having an in-an-interview feeling\
Don\'92t ask \'93leading questions\'94 (how will I recognize those when I\'92m asking them?)\
Non-leading questions include when, where, how, why, \'93walk me through\'85\'94, \'93tell me about your best/worst/most recent experience with\'85\'94, \'93how much in a typical month do\'85\'94, \'93tell me more about\'85\'94\
Try to distill Facts, Feelings, possible Value Systems, influences they\'92ve identified (friends, location, culture)\
Be ready to adjust each conversation as it happens instead of having a rigid set of questions\
\
Questions:\
When did you learn to program? What interested you? Where did you spend most of your time before learning to program?\
Do remember the first time you got feedback on a piece of code? What was helpful? What expectations and anxieties did you have?\
Do you remember the first time you reviewed? What urges did you have? Habits you\'92ve dropped since?\
Has your review style changed? \
What work do you do / languages do you use and does that affect the feedback you give?\
Do you have benchmarks / a flow in what you look for? Do you review in stages?\
What makes a code review successful?\
If you review in different ways, what factors do you consider when deciding how to review? Experience? How code is used? Type of team? Open source vs. work?\
Do you ask reviewers for anything specific on an particular samples?\
Any times when something clicked for you, either in a specific review (what helped?) or about reviewing itself?\
